\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\lang1025\qj 18.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 This interpretation disregards the clear and unambiguous wording of subsection 13A(2). The \'91golden rule\'92 of statutory interpretation is that the words of a statute must be given their plain meaning unless the words used are ambiguous, vague, misleading or 
would result in an absurdity, in which case the court may deviate from that meaning to avoid such absurdity.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s9{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs12\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 See Venter v R 1907 TS 910 at 914; Standard Bank Investment Corporation Ltd v Competition Commission and Others; Liberty Life Association of Africa v Competition Commission  2000 (2) SA 797 (SCA) at paragraphs 16-20. }}}
{\*\cs12\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up10\rtlch\af5\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177 } In our view, the wording of section 16(1)(b) is very clear and the plain meaning of the words used therein results in no absurdity. The use of the
 word \'93or\'94 at the end of subsection 13A(2)(a) and the proviso to subsection 13A(2)(b){\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s9{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs20\lang1033\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033{\*\cs12\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 The proviso is that the persons listed in subsection 13A(2)(b) are required to be served where there is  no registered trade union representing a substantial number of the employees of the merging firms.}}}
{\*\cs12\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up10\rtlch\af5\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177 } clearly indicates that the persons listed in 13A(2)(b) (i.e. employees or their representatives) are only required to be served a notice where there are no trade unions 
referred to in 13A(2)(a). A party to a merger is therefore not required to serve the merger notice on all the persons listed in subsection 13A(2) but to one of them only. As noted above, it is common cause that TAWU and SATAWU are the registered trade unio
ns representing the employees of KZT. It was not disputed by the complainants that these unions represent a \'91substantial\'92 number of KZT employees as contemplated in section 13A(2)(a). In the circumstances, only TAWU and SATAWU were required to be served th
e merger notice in this case and they alone are entitled to bring these proceedings. The fact that they elected not to do so does not make the applicants\'92 case any stronger. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\lang1025\qj 19.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 The applicants\'92 contention that they enjoyed {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i locus standi} in the Commission\'92s proceedings is not correct. Only persons contemplated in section 13A(2) of the Act, which as we have pointed out the applicants are not, enjoy such a right. The applicants\'92 parti
cipation in the Commission\'92s proceedings amounted to no more than the making of representations about the merger, which any concerned member of the public is entitled to make.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s9{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs12\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 See section 13B(3) of the Act.}}}
{\*\cs12\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up10\rtlch\af5\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177 } Making a submission did not confer {\rtlch\ai\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i locus standi} upon them nor does it make any 
difference that in making their submissions they completed form CC 5(1). When section 16(1)(b) refers to participation in the Commission\'92s proceedings it means participation by persons required to be notified in terms of 13A(2). In this sense the applicant
s, despite making submissions, were not participants in the Commission\'92s proceedings in the manner contemplated in section 16. The applicants\'92 involvement in the Commission\'92s proceedings can not confer upon them a {\rtlch\ai\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i locus standi} which the Act does not give t
hem anymore than it would to any other person who makes representations to the Commission, as is frequently the case, such as a customer or competitor of the merging parties.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\lang1025\qj 20.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 We turn now to the applicants\'92 argument that their constitutional rights may be violated by the interpretation adopted above. The applicants are correct that we are bound by section 1(2) of the Act to interpret the Act in a manner consistent with the Const
itution. We do not consider that the interpretation of section 16(1)(b) adopted herein is inconsistent with any provision of the Constitution. Section 16(1)(b) gives priority to represent employees\'92 views to the registered trade union, which is the recogni
sed collective bargaining unit{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s9\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs12\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 The following dictum by Centlivres JA in {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i Amalgamated Engineering Union v Minister of Labour and Another} 1949 (4) SA 908 (A), although made in the context of the Industrial Conciliation Act, is pertinent: \'93The whole idea underlying the trade union system \'85
 is that the trade union concerned should act as the spokesperson for its members whenever a dispute arises between employers and employees. The act encourages collective bargaining\'85 To insist that whenever a dispute arises between employers and employees,
 an individual employer or employee should set the statutory machinery in motion for the purpose of settling the dispute, would tend to defeat the object which the legislature had in mind, viz. to facilitate the settlement of disputes, for it is obvious th
at what the legislature had in mind was that employees should use the services of the trade union of which they are members and that employers should use the services of the employers' organisations to which they belong.\'94 See also {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i Steel And Engineering Ind
ustries Federation And Others v National Union of Metalworkers Of South Africa }(1) 1993 (4) SA 190 (T) }}}
{\*\cs12\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up10\rtlch\af5\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af5\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177 }. The right is given to individual employees or their representatives in default, where there is no registered trade union. The fact that a trade union may not participate in a merger proceeding does not mean that it was pass
ive in enforcing its members' rights. It is equally possible that the trade union considered that the merger was nevertheless in its members\'92 best interests or that opposition would be futile. The legislative policy of preferring the collective bargaining 
unit to the individual seems to us a sound one as if every employee was given these rights, merger adjudication would be rendered impractical. }
