\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\lang1025\qj 21.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s3\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 The applicants seek to use section 34 of the Constitution to invoke a right which the clear language of the Competition Act does not afford them. Whilst the application of section 34 is still in its infancy, what case law there is, relates to the constitut
ionality of impediments to enforcing ones rights, for example, prescription periods and  onerous costs provisions, etc.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s9{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs12\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 See Chaskalson et al, {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i Constitutional Law of South Africa}, (Juta) 1999, pages 25-23 to 25-24. }}}
